(define "AtSitesInfluence"  
 (forEach
  (expand
   (sites Occupied by:Mover) 
   steps:2
  )
  if:(or
   (and
    (= (mover) (who at:(site)))
    (= #1 (var "MaxDistance"))
   )
   (and
    (!= (mover) (who at:(site)))
    (=
     #1
     ("NeighborCountOfAt" (mover) (site))
)))))

(metadata
 (info
  {
   (description "Throngs originally was a highly abstracted wargame (territorial invasion game) for two players. It is typically played on the intersections of a triangular grid, using Go stones. It was a double-move game: each player takes 2 full turns in succession before the next player takes control. 
            
      Movement: The game is distinguished by the way the power of a moving piece is determined according to the pieces around it: A piece can move as far as the difference in count of the friends and enemies in its immediate vicinity. 
            
      I have adapted this game for several reasons: 
      1. People still have difficulty learning the rules for movement.
      2. Double moves complicate the learning and play.
      3. I like to make games that can be ported to other grid types.
      4. I have been using Ludii to implement and test the game, but Ludii does not handle the existing movement rule in a way that can be easily and efficiently scripted and processed, making the script very complicated and the ai weak.
      Additionally the rule is poorly defined for snub geometries.
      
      I address these as follows
      The turn rule is simplified by applying the influence at the turn's start without deductions for entry and captures. This is replaces with a distinction between the influence of the location and the influence of its vicinity. The new approach allows tuning the capturing strength to matched different grid types. It also preserves or extends the increase in range for entering moves that was added in the single turn variant.

The original movement (straight jumps with direction changes at empty locations) functioned to gradually limit access to opponent controlled areas as the game progressed. However 'straight' is not defined on Snub-square boards, so that rule is not easily extensible. The rule has now been replaced with a rule which states that stones can step in any direction up to the distance limit, provided that they end at an empty space without having stepped over 2 enemy stones consecutively.

With these changes, the game can be adapted to regular grids with different levels of connection - from the nodes of a hex grid with 3 neighbors eah, up to the 8 neighbors of a square grid with diagonals - and possibly beyond.

The game is robust, so the tuning the center value need not be precise. For experimental purposes, my script contains an option to either boost or reduce the central value from the prefered standard value.

Additionally, due to the fact that movenent depends on local influence, the geometry of the board edges has significant effects on tactics and strategy. Therefore I have designed and included additional boards with special edges for each of the grid types. All the boards have an odd number of nodes and each type is offered in a small (55-81) and large (107-133) size.

The result is this modified offering of a family of Throngs games called: 'Throngs on the Grid'
      "
   ) 
   
   (rules 
"Goal: A player's overall goal is to achieve a majority of stones when the board is full. 
    
The board starts with Red placing a stone one step away from the edge, followed by Blue also placing one step from the edge, but not adjacent to Red.

Alternatively, the first player may ask the 2nd player to make a pie offer of 3 stones (one Red and two Blue). Regular play then starts with Red.

Play

To start your turn, choose a location with positive influence (see Calulating Influence under the 'Option' for your board below). The amount of this influence will limit how far your stone will be able to move.

Depending on the location chosen, either:
-- Place a new active stone to the empty location;
-- Capture the opposing stone there, by replacing it with your new active stone; or
-- Use your stone that is already there to move.

Your active stone now optionally takes a series of adjacent steps that must end on an empty location within the distance limit imposed by its initial influence value. 

Movement restriction:
The stone may not move across two enemy stones in succession.

Note: There are also two restrictions that prevent stalling moves:
-- On a capturing turn, you are not allowed to move your stone to a location where it may then be captured on the opponent's next turn.
-- You are not allowed to move your existing stone to a location where you could simply place a new stone. 

(These restrictions might prevent some starting locations from being selected.)

Voluntary passing is not allowed; your move must change the state of the game.

The game ends when the one player can keep the other player's stones out of more than half the board. (This application counts stones that can immediately be captured, as captured.)
    "
   )

   (source "<a href=\"https://boardgamegeek.com/thread/2452882/throngs-new-attempt-describe-how-play\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"style1\" style=\"color: #0000EE\" />BGG Forum</a>")
   (version "1.3.14")
   (classification "board/space/territory")
   (author "Dale W. Walton")
   (credit "Dale W. Walton 2026-05-27")
   (date "18-11-2019")
  }
 )
 (graphics
  {
//         (show Edges Diagonal Hidden) 
   (show Edges <Grid:show>)
   (board Style Graph)
   (player Colour P1 (colour DarkRed))
   (player Colour P2 (colour LightBlue))
   (piece Scale P1 "Ball" .8) // 0.93)
   (piece Scale P2 "Ball" .8) // 0.93)
   (piece Colour P1 "Ball" value:1 fillColour:(colour 30 30 30 30 ) secondaryColour:(colour 0 0 0) )
   (piece Colour P2 "Ball" value:1 fillColour:(colour 255 255 255 30) secondaryColour:(colour 0 0 0))
   (board Background image:"Square.svg" fillColour:(colour 230 230 230) edgeColour:(colour 230 230 230) scale:1.26 offsetX:-.01) // offsetY:<Board:centering>)
   (board StyleThickness InnerEdges 1.75)
   (board StyleThickness OuterEdges 4.0)
   (board StyleThickness InnerVertices 0.7)
   (board StyleThickness OuterVertices 0.7)
   (board Colour InnerVertices (colour 120 110 100))
   (board Colour OuterVertices (colour DarkGrey))
   (board Colour InnerEdges (colour 200 200 200 255))
   (board Colour OuterEdges (colour Grey))
   (no Sunken)
   <Graphics:showPotentials>
   <Graphics:showTerritory>
  }
))
